english:
  title: 'A Parting Gift for Song Jagyo: A Preface'
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Choi Sojae came and spoke thus: "Both Pyo and Yeom Dongjung descended from the school of Lord Song of Sungsan. Now their grandson Jagyo has likewise been chosen by Dongjung, and he returns to pay his respects to his ancestor at Sungsan. We gather to see him off. Dongjung, too, dares not hold back and joins us. Surely we should write something to mark this departure—a poem or prose. We are not without such skill, yet we fear our words lack the weight to move our honored lineage. Though you are of the younger generation, you sit among us in the Dragon Head Society. Your eyes perceive Jagyo as no ordinary man. We beg you—grace him with a single word."

    I replied: I am old and infirm; my memory fails me daily. Yet my patron, the Minister Ikjae, had a grandson Lee Jeongdang who descended from his master's student, Minister An. The grandson of Geunjae Minister An, the official Kyeonggong, descended from his grandfather's student Chamberlain Hong. My own son, studying at our gates, became the student of Han Cheongseong, who was himself a student of Minister Gajung. Thus Jagyo's connection to Dongjung is no mere chance. The patronage lineage flourished in the Tang, though it wavered in Song's twilight. Yet the blood of literature flows with heaven and earth—how could the rise and fall of ages create discord in such a stream?

    Since the Middle Kingdom knew upheaval, our Eastern lands have revered the scholarly and exalted the literary, no different from ages of peace. So do they praise the glory of those who lead in letters, the beauty of advancement—none can withhold admiration, finding none to equal them. Ah, how the nation's refinement and the people's rectitude remain undiminished from old. Though I am worn with age and sickness, I unworthily sit among the ennobled, and bearing responsibility for history and letters, I spend day and night hoping to inspire talent and spread the royal transformation.

    I cannot refuse Sojae's request, nor should I fail to record Dongjung's virtue and the honor of the Song line. So I set aside my humble pen and write this farewell, adding: 'The glory Dongjung brings to his family lacks only one thing—that your ancestor could not come. When autumn cools and you ride home with steady hands upon the reins, I too shall join the gathering once more. Then it will be no honor for Dongjung alone.'"
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'Dragon Head Society (용두회): A scholarly gathering or association, likely of officials and literati.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Patronage lineage (은문): The tradition of students inheriting positions or honor through their masters'' lineage, extending across generations.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'The Middle Kingdom (중원) and Eastern lands: Refers to China and Korea respectively.'
  - key: ''
    value: Lee Saek's closing sentiment expresses hope that Song Jagyo's grandfather will eventually visit Korea, allowing Lee Saek to participate in the family's celebration.
